Servilius Caepio (de am. 596), and whose intimate friendship with Scipio Africanus the younger (de am. 1 5 4, de rep. 15 18, deofl 15 118, de or. 11 5 aa) is constantly spoken of by Cicero as an example of what friendship should be. He distinguished himself against Viriathus in Spain tac. 145 (11 5 40), buthe was more of a statesman than a soldier and more of 1 philoso her than a statesman. He imbibed the doctrines of the Stoic school m Diogenes Babylonius and Panaetius, and was a friend of Polybius and Terence, whose plays were by some ascribed to him. He afterwards became a staunch snpporter of the optimates. The treatise deamicitia is called Laelius after him (11 5 31) because he is the chief interlocutos in the dialogue.
